, Lewis highlights the ethnographic details of legal proceedings as she demonstrates how Indians, in particular, came to be the masters of witchcraft, a domain of power that drew on gendered and hegemonic caste distinctions to complicate the colonial hierarchy. She also reveals the ways in which blacks, mulattoes, and mestizos mediated between Spaniards and Indians, alternatively reinforcing Spanish authority and challenging it through alliances with Indians. Bringing to life colonial subjects as they testified about their experiences, Hall of Mirrors discloses a series of contradictions that complicate easy distinctions between subalterns and elites, resistance and power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCastezMexicoxHistory. 0aPower (Social sciences)zMexicoxHistory. 0aWitchcraftzMexicoxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aMignolo, Walter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverblatt, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385158zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822385158423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822385158.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles